<h2>Getting started</h2>

<p>Include the Flickity <code>.css</code> and <code>.js</code> files in your site.</p>

``` html
<link rel="stylesheet" href="/path/to/flickity.css" media="screen">
```

``` html
<script src="/path/to/flickity.pkgd.min.js"></script>
```

<p>Flickity works on a container carousel element with a group of cell elements.</p>

``` html
<div class="main-carousel">
  <div class="carousel-cell">...</div>
  <div class="carousel-cell">...</div>
  <div class="carousel-cell">...</div>
  ...
</div>
```

<p>There are several ways to initialize Flickity.</p>

{{! ----------------------------------------------------------------- }}

<h3>Initialize with jQuery</h3>

<p>You can use Flickity as a jQuery plugin: <code>$(<span class="string">'selector'</span>).flickity()</code>.</p>

``` js
$('.main-carousel').flickity({
  // options
  cellAlign: 'left',
  contain: true
});
```

{{! ----------------------------------------------------------------- }}

<h3>Initialize with vanilla JavaScript</h3>

<p>You can use Flickity with vanilla JS: <code><span class="keyword">new</span> Flickity( elem )</code>. The <code>Flickity()</code> constructor accepts two arguments: the carousel element and an options object.</p>

``` js
var elem = document.querySelector('.main-carousel');
var flkty = new Flickity( elem, {
  // options
  cellAlign: 'left',
  contain: true
});

// element argument can be a selector string
//   for an individual element
var flkty = new Flickity( '.main-carousel', {
  // options
});
```

{{! ----------------------------------------------------------------- }}

<h3>Initialize with HTML</h3>

<p>You can initialize Flickity in HTML, without writing any JavaScript. Add <code>data-flickity</code> attribute to the carousel element. <a href="options.html">Options</a> can be set in its value.</p>


``` html
<div class="main-carousel" data-flickity='{ "cellAlign": "left", "contain": true }'>
```

<div class="call-out">
  <p>Options set in HTML must be valid JSON. Keys need to be quoted, for example <code>"cellAlign":</code>. Note that the attribute value uses single quotes <code>'</code>, but the JSON entities use double-quotes <code>"</code>.</p>
</div>

